Tip:
Mass conservation
During a change of state, the number of particles doesn’t change — they’re
just arranged differently. This means that mass is conserved — none of it is
lost when the substance changes state. If you set up your experiment so none
of the particles can escape (e.g. by collecting all of the water vapour produced
when a liquid boils), you can measure the mass during a change of state and
see that it remains constant.
If you reverse a change of state (e.g. freeze a substance that has been melted),
the particles return to how they were before the change of state. So the
substance returns to its original form and gets back its original properties.
This is different to most chemical changes.
